Analyzing the blue dropoff data

setwd("~/Downloads")
ccd <-read.csv("all_datasets_dropoff_data.csv")
ccd$ind = 1:nrow(ccd)
ccp<-ccd %>% pivot_longer(-ind,names_to=c("grams","dataset"),names_pattern="([^_]*)_([^_]*)_.*", values_to="bleu")
ccp1=ccp[ccp$grams=='uni',]
ccp3=ccp[ccp$grams=='tri',]

First boxplots broken down by unigrams and trigrams, and then datset

 ggplot(ccp,aes(dataset,bleu))+geom_boxplot()+facet_grid(rows=vars(grams))

OK, so clearly, for uni grams, nl is on the low end, along with docstring2. (why docstring2?). For trigrams, nl is at the high end.

Now lets try some lines. Colored by dataset, and gridded by gram length

ggplot(ccp,aes(ind,bleu,color=dataset))+facet_grid(cols=vars(grams))+geom_line(size=1.0)

ggplot(ccp,aes(,bleu))+geom_boxplot()+facet_grid(rows=vars(grams),cols=vars(dataset=='nl'))

So we can see this:

  1. On unigrams, NL is affected a lot (not the most)
  2. On Trigrams, NL is affected the least.

Trying some linear models

lmuni<-lm(data=ccp1,bleu~ind+(dataset=='nl'))
lmtri<-lm(data=ccp3,bleu~ind+(dataset=='nl'))

So, the results are consistent. When controlling for the number of grams removed, for unigrams, nl has negative effect compared to the others, for trigrams it has a postive effect. Both statistically signifiacnt.
